The '''mangrove pitta''' ('''''Pitta megarhyncha''''') is a species of [[passerine]] [[bird]] in the family [[Pittidae]] native to the eastern [[Indian subcontinent]] and western [[Southeast Asia]]. It is part of a [[superspecies]] where it is placed with the [[Indian pitta]], the [[fairy pitta]] and the [[blue-winged pitta]] but has no recognized subspecies. A colourful bird, it has a black head with brown crown, white throat, greenish upper parts, buff underparts and reddish vent area. Its range extends from India to Malaysia and Indonesia. It is found in [[mangrove]] and [[Nypa fruticans|nipa palm]] forests where it feeds on crustaceans, mollusks and insects. Its call, sometimes rendered as ''wieuw-wieuw'', is sung from a high perch on a mangrove tree.

==Taxonomy==
The mangrove pitta was first described by German [[ornithologist]] [[Hermann Schlegel]] in 1863.{{sfn|Sen|Zöckler|Singal|Jayadevan|2016|p=1—4}} Its species name is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] words ''mega-'' "large", and ''rhynchos'' "beak". It forms a [[superspecies]] with the [[Indian pitta]] (''P. brachyura''), [[fairy pitta]] (''P. nympha'') and [[blue-winged pitta]] (''P. moluccensis''). Alternate common names include: Larger blue-winged/Malay pitta, Brève des palétuviers (in French), Große Blauflügelpitta (in German), and Pita de Manglar (in Spanish).{{sfn|Hoyo|1992|p=158}} There are no recognized subspecies.<ref name=sound>{{cite web|title=Species overview: Mangrove Pitta (''Pitta megarhyncha'') |url=https://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Pitta-megarhyncha | publisher=Xeno-Canto Asia|access-date=4 June 2011}}</ref>

==Description==
[[File:Mangrove Pitta.ogg|thumb|left|Kuala Selangor, Malaysia, Aug 1994]]
Measuring {{convert|180|to(-)|210|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length, the mangrove pitta has a black head with a buff-coloured crown, white chin and buff underparts. The shoulders and mantle are greenish and the vent is reddish. Juveniles have similar patterned plumage but are duller. It resembles the blue-winged pitta but can be distinguished by its much heavier bill.{{sfn|Robson|2005|p=76}} Its call, transcribed as ''wieuw-wieuw'' has been noted to be "more slurred" than the blue-winged pitta.{{sfn|Robson|2005|p=76}}

==Distribution and habitat==
The mangrove pitta is native to the countries of: [[Bangladesh]], [[India]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], [[Myanmar]], [[Singapore]], and [[Thailand]] (primarily the west coast of the southern Thai peninsula).<ref name=BirdLife>{{cite web|title=Mangrove Pitta ''Pitta megarhyncha''
|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=4020| publisher=[[BirdLife International]]|access-date=4 June 2011}}</ref>
{{sfn|Sen|Zöckler|Singal|Jayadevan|2016|p=1—4}}<ref name=thai>{{cite web|title=Pittas of Thailand|url=https://www.thaibirding.com/features/pittas.htm| publisher=Thai Birding|access-date=4 June 2011}}</ref> Its natural [[habitat]] is specialised and restriction to subtropical or tropical [[mangrove]] [[forest]]s and [[Nypa fruticans|Nipa palm]] stands.{{sfn|Lok|Khor|Lim|Subaraj|2009|p=158}} It is threatened by [[habitat loss]]. Its diet consists of [[crustacean]]s, [[mollusk]]s and terrestrial insects.<ref name=BirdLife/>{{sfn|Sen|Zöckler|Singal|Jayadevan|2016|p=1—4}}{{sfn|Lok|Khor|Lim|Subaraj|2009|p=158,162}}

==Behaviour==
[[File:Mangrove Pitta.jpg|thumb|Mangrove pitta at [[Bhitarkanika National Park]], [[Odisha]], [[India]]]]
While all pittas are noted for being difficult to study and spot in the wild, the mangrove pitta is one of the easier ones to spot as it sits high up in mangrove trees and calls.<ref name=thai/> A tape recording of its call will often bring it forth.{{sfn|Strange|2000|p=219}} It tends to be vocal while brooding but quiet at other times.{{sfn|Lok|Khor|Lim|Subaraj|2009|p=158}} A recent paper from [[Sunderbans Tiger Reserve]] reported swimming behavior of the species.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Bhattacharya |first1=M. |last2=Ongole |first2=S. |title=Swimming behaviour observed in a Mangrove Pitta ''Pitta megarhyncha'' in Sundarbans, West Bengal, India |url=https://indianbirds.in/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/IB_21_3_Bhattacharya_Ongole_MangrovePitta.pdf |journal=[[Indian Birds]] |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=96A |access-date=30 August 2025 |via=}}</ref>

